6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both Aevo and Vertex calculate funding rates hourly using standard perpetual swap mechanics based on premium/discount to spot. Aevo operates on its own rollup with specialized infrastructure for options and perps, potentially creating unique rate dynamics from combined product exposure. Vertex uses Arbitrum's infrastructure with a hybrid on-chain/off-chain model that may exhibit different rate volatility patterns. The funding rate calculation methodology is similar, but settlement timing and gas costs differ due to their distinct infrastructure choices."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has lower trading fees for funding arbitrage?","answer":"Vertex has significantly lower taker fees at 0.03% compared to Aevo's 0.05%, while maker fees are identical at 0.02%. This makes Vertex more cost-effective for frequent arbitrage trades."},{"question":"How do the funding rate calculation methods differ?","answer":"Both exchanges use standard hourly funding rate calculations based on perpetual-spot premium. However, Aevo's rollup infrastructure and combined options exposure may create unique rate dynamics compared to Vertex's Arbitrum-based system."},{"question":"Which platform offers better liquidity for large arbitrage positions?","answer":"Vertex generally provides deeper liquidity pools due to its focus on core perpetual products, while Aevo's liquidity is spread across options and perps, potentially making large position execution more challenging."},{"question":"Are there infrastructure risks that affect funding arbitrage?","answer":"Aevo faces rollup centralization risks and potential sequencer downtime, while Vertex depends on Arbitrum's infrastructure and its own sequencer reliability. Both have single points of failure that could impact arbitrage execution timing."}]}]
